        {
            "__type__": "Note",
            "fields": [
                "In {{c1::1628}}, {{c2::William Harvey}} provided the first full and accurate description of {{c3::blood circulation}} in the human body . But many people doubted his theory because he was not able to find the means by which blood passed from the arterial to the venous system. It was {{c4::Marcello Malpighi}} that discovered the “missing link” in {{c5::1661}}. Using the newly invented microscope, he discovered the network of tiny capillaries that are {{c6::10}} times thinner than human hairs and link {{c7::arteries}} and {{c7::veins}}.<br><br><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\">Ref: The Medicine Book: Big Ideas Simply Explained - DK - 2021 → pg-66, 70-73.</span>",
                ""
            ],
            "guid": "A7X8C[#:k4",
            "note_model_uuid": "56671b6a-b205-11ef-9801-d0abd5c278c3",
            "tags": []
